  <static seed="1594" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations55.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{7}{y}-\frac{6}{y-2}} = -2 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-2,\frac{7}{2}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of fractions, we multiply each term in this equation by the common denominator, which is <m>{y\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)}</m> in this example.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp {\frac{7}{y}-\frac{6}{y-2}} = -2 \\
   \amp {\frac{7}{y}y\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)-\frac{6}{y-2}y\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)} ={-2y\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)} \\
   \amp {7\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)-6y} = {-2y^{2}+4y} \\
   \amp {7y-14-6y} = {-2y^{2}+4y} \\
   \amp {y-14} = {-2y^{2}+4y} \\
   \amp {y-14+2y^{2}-4y} = 0 \\
   \amp {2y^{2}-3y-14} = 0 \\
   \amp ({2y-7})({y+2})=0 \\
   \amp {2y-7}=0 \:\: or\:\: {y+2}=0 \\
   \amp y={{\frac{7}{2}}} \:\: or\:\: y={-2}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><alert>Checking</alert></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp y = 0 \amp \;\amp  y - 2=0 \\
   \amp y=0 \amp \;\amp  y=2
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>0</m> and <m>2</m> from the solution set. There is no conflict with those two solutions we got, so the final solution is <m>y={{\frac{7}{2}}}</m> and <m>y={-2}</m>.</p>
</solution>
